Running user-defined functions in R on Earth observation data in cloud back-ends

Pramit Ghosh, Florian Lahn, Soeren Gebbert, Matthias Mohr and Edzer Pebesma

Institute for Geoinformatics, WWU Muenster, Germany

08.12.2018 at Geomundus, '18 in Lisbon, Portugal

Have you ever used satellite images?




Let's have a show of hands!

So, what's the "traditional" workflow for satellite images?

Usually, it involves the following

  • Selecting appropriate sensors
  • Downloading it locally
  • Processing and analysis


What is the problem with this?

Apparently, nothing! But, imagine processing a 30 years long time-series of LANDSAT data, say to calculate NDVI.

New problems

  • Bandwidth
  • Computing power

Challenges

  • Rapid launch of new satellites
  • Increase in resolution

EO data is big data and alternate workflows are required.

How to deal with this problem?

Upload the code and let the processing take place in the cloud instead. Advantages:

  • Overcomes bandwith limitations
  • More computing power

Will allow the back-ends to be used by client nodes using different programing languages, mediated by a common API

openEO: Open Earth Observation

The openEO project does exactly that.

Develops an API to allow clients using Javascript, R or Python to send processing requests to cloud back-ends

User-defined Functions (UDFs) in openEO

UDFs allow to users operating the client to run their own custom code on EO data too instead of only those natively available in the cloud back-ends.

UDFs in R

R package openEO.R.UDF (Ghosh and Lahn, 2018) implements three strategies to develop services for running UDFs on EO data using the stars package (Pebesma, 2018)

Strategy 1: File-based service

  • Data (GeoTIFF files) and a look-up table (CSV file) written to disk
  • Converts data to stars object, executes user's R script and write resultant object to disk
  • Practically, the UDF service is a part of the back-end

Strategy 2: RESTful web service using JSON arrays

  • Data sent to a web service by writing pixel values in JSON arrays
  • Data sent and results received in the form of openEO UDF API compliant HTTP POST requests and responses respectively
  • RESTful server has two end-points
    • /udf exposes only a list of values to the UDF
    • /udf/raw exposes the entire stars object to the UDF

Strategy 3: RESTful web service using base64 encoded string

  • Similar to Strategy 2 with an endpoint /udf/binary
  • Except data represented as a base64 encoded string of a compressed ZIP file containing GeoTIFF files
  • This string is embedded along with other metadata as a JSON in the POST body

Containerization using Docker

  • The R package has been containerized using Docker (Merkel, 2014) for reproducibility and testing the web services
  • It is available publicly on Docker Hub at the following URL: https://hub.docker.com/r/pramitghosh/openeo.r.udf/

Future Directions

openEO aims to pursue UDFs for EO data processing in the cloud. Some challenges ahead:

  • In order for the UDF service(s) to handle big data, it needs to be scalable. For this, the data from the backend could be sliced into smaller chunks. The slicing strategy would be based on which dimension of the EO data cube the UDF is being applied on. These smaller chunks could be sent to multiple UDF services for parallel processing in the cloud and then stichting the individual results back.
  • Further development of the openEO UDF API for R and Python
